s and Natures -- tCHAPTER 10 A Revolutionary Civilization: National Parks, Transnational Exchanges and the Construction of Modern Mexico -- tCHAPTER 11 Parks without Wilderness, Wilderness without Parks? Assigning National Park Status to Dutch Manmade Landscapes and Colonial Game Reserves -- tCHAPTER 12 Globalizing Nature: National Parks, Tiger Reserves and Biosphere Reserves in Independent India -- tCHAPTER 13 Slovenia’s Triglav National Park: From Imperial Borderland to National Ethnoscape -- tEPILOGUE National Parks, Civilization and Globalization -- tSelect Bibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNational parks are one of the most important and successful institutions in global environmentalism. Since their first designation in the United States in the 1860s and 1870s they have become a global phenomenon. The development of these ecological and political systems cannot be understood as a simple reaction to mounting environmental problems, nor can it be explained by the spread of environmental sensibilities. Shifting the focus from the usual emphasis on national parks in the United States, this volume adopts an historical and transnational perspective on the global geography of protected areas and its changes over time. It focuses especially on the actors, networks, mechanisms, arenas, and institutions responsible for the global spread of the national park and the associated utilization and mobilization of asymmetrical relationships of power and knowledge, contributing to scholarly discussions of globalization and the emergence of global environmental institutions and governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEnvironmental protectionxHistory. 0aEnvironmentalismxHistory. 0aGlobalization